task.summary: Default task
Update approach in ContainsDuplicate2
Add approach in ContainsDuplicate3
Add alternate approach of pushing numbers instead of indices in SlidingWindowMaximum and add comment on how does it handles duplicate elements
Simplify logic in DistributeNCandiesToKPeople
Add approach in FindKthBitInNthBinaryString, tricky binary search and index handling
Remove initial solution and add approach in tricky question MaxPathSum
Update variable name in TimeNeededToInformAllEmployees
Add constraints in problem statement

Add another solution in PathSum3 by extending the path from children and starting a new path from current node before returning to parent.
Learnings -- Paths in a tree can be visualized as subarray problem.
Add problem statement and update approach
Add errichto's template of binary search, does not work for finding min element in rotated sorted array containing duplicates.
Simplify code and add approach in find no of ways to achieve target sum
Add clarifications/gotcha in generation of ugly numbers
Solve medium find the start of the cycle in linked list using warshall floyd algorithm

Solve medium find all possible partitions of a string such that each partition is a palindrome by backtracking.
Important to understand the time complexity of this solution, there can be maximum n-1 cuts and each cut can either be picked or be skipped, so total is 2^(n-1)

Solve hard and tricky find the kth sorted permutation of the given input array using greedy + maths.
Backtracking solution is trivial and requires generating all k permutations of the input array.
Greedy solution fixes one digit at a time of the result; by figuring out how many permutations does a digit can generate if it's the first digit of the permutation. We recursively fix one digit and are left with n-1 digits.
Solve easy find whether any permutation of the input string can be a palindrome or not by checking the count of characters with odd frequency.

Solve hard and tricky find whether a word is entirely composed of two or more words from dictionary. Similar to previously solved WordBreak1 but gives TLE for me somehow.
Solved it using Trie to quickly find whether the current prefix is valid prefix or not. Important to sort the words because a word can only be made from shorter words.

Solve medium and tricky find number of longest increasing subsequences. Need to store the count of LIS ending at any index, while updating the length of LIS at current index, reset or increment the count depending upon the current length.
If current length > currently stored length, reset the count, else if current length == currently stored length, increment the count

Solve medium find length of the longest consecutive sequence in a binary tree by passing information to the child.
Child needs to know what is the length of the consecutive sequence present at parent and decide whether it can extend it or not.

Solve medium and a bit tricky find length of the longest increasing/decreasing consecutive sequence in a binary tree
Since both increasing/decreasing sequence needs to be considered, parent node must be aware of the longest sequence ending/beginning at child node. This will ensure parent has the information to choose either of the path.

Solve hard and a bit tricky to reduce time complexity, find two nodes whose values are swapped in a bst.
This is similar to finding two elements in nearly sorted array that have been swapped. It's a classical problem that can be done in linear time without sorting the entire input using two pointers

Solve medium and very interesting low level implementation problem, encode a list of strings to a single string that can be decoded to convert into list of strings.
There are multiple ways to solve this question, use a delimiter outside of input char range, or escape the chosen delimiter if present in the input or use chunked transfer encoding

Solve easy meeting rooms, check whether there is a conflict in the appointment.
Leveraged prior learnings of MyCalendar1. Can also be done by sorting the entire array and then checking for conflicts.

Solve medium but very tricky to optimize sentence screen fitting, fit a sentence into a grid such that a word can't be split across two rows.
Learnings -- Deal with questions related to finding no of repetitions in a infinitely repeating sequence

Solve hard find all possible subsequences of a target string in the source string by recursion.
Initially I thought to implement it by storing indices of all target characters and look for a greater index than previous chosen index but sadly it timed out. (Similar to MinWindowSubsequence)
Later I thought to implement it the classic way of solving problems related to two string, compare characters at two indices and update indices accordingly.

Solve hard find all possible subsequences of a target string in the source string by recursion.
Initially I thought to implement it by storing indices of all target characters and look for a greater index than previous chosen index but sadly it timed out. (Similar to MinWindowSubsequence)
Later I thought to implement it the classic way of solving problems related to two string, compare characters at two indices and update indices accordingly.
Simplify treeMap solution by directly adding element to the map if map is empty.
Simplify code by removing complicated initial code and add approach in find maximum width of a binary tree
Solve classical hard problem merge k sorted linked list using priority queue

Solve hard problem find the longest substring with balanced '(' and ')' using two pass algorithm.
First use stack to mark balanced indices, then find the longest subarray with all balanced index.
Tried to initially solve the question via a lot of approaches, sliding window, prefix sum but it failed.
This question can also be solved by using DP, care must be taken to carry forward the results which I missed.

Solve medium sudoku solver using classic backtracking algorithm. Try to place candidates on an emptyIndex and recur for the remaining empty indices. If none of the candidates are safe to place, backtrack and unset a previously placed candidate.
Care must be taken to properly backtrack all the associated datastructures as there are many in this case.

Solve medium partition a binary tree into two subtree with equal sum using two pass algorithm. First find the total sum and then for each parent, check if the child subtree has half the total sum. If yes, cut that edge.
Care must be taken to disambiguate null nodes vs nodes with val 0

Solve medium tricky problem find longest substring with all unique characters repeating >=k times.
Sliding window technique is really odd and seems hacky. Recursive solution to create splits at invalid characters makes sense.
Solve easy find average of top 5 scores of each student using counting sort.
Rename file to match problem statement

Solve easy but tricky to optimize design a stack that supports popMax() along with usual push() and pop().
To identify largest value in the stack, we need to use treeMap but in order to delete the largest node in o(1) time, we need a way to directly delete a node. Only DLL supports constant time deletion. So need to model the stack as a DLL.

Solve medium and tricky find the longest substring such that the all characters of the substring can be made equal in <= k operations
First identify whats the min no of operations required to make all characters same, then use sliding window to find longest such window.
Learnings -- Longest window vs shortest window -- sliding window implementation is different in both the cases. In former, you keep expanding until window becomes invalid, then you start shrinking until it's valid. In latter, you expand until you find a valid window, then you start shrinking until it becomes invalid.

Solve medium find the longest subarray that can be transformed to all 1's in <= k operations (0 can be transformed to 1 in one operation)
Problem reduces to finding the longest subarray with num zeroes <= k, use the standard sliding window paradigm for implementation.
Simplify code by rewriting it to standard sliding window paradigm, keep increasing the window until it becomes invalid, then keep shrinking the window until it becomes valid again.

Solve hard find longest substring containing at most k distinct characters using sliding window.
Keep track of the distinct chars in the current window, if it exceeds k, continue to shrink the window from the left, until it becomes valid again.

Solve easy but tricky greedy problem, given the initial position of the chips, find the min cost to move them to the same position.
Min cost can be found if one of the initial state is chosen as the end state, so choose all of the initial position as the target position and find the total cost to bring remaining chips to it's position.
This n^2 pattern seems to be pretty common. Can be done in linear time but ....

Solve medium and tricky find nodes that can reach both pacific and atlantic ocean by doing DFS from the oceans and not from the inner nodes.
Finally I was able to understand why doing DFS in SurroundedRegions from inner nodes resulted in WA -- due to circular dependency.

Add recursive solution similar to knapsack for TwoCityScheduling problem. Every person has two option, go to city A or city B.
Constraint is that only half of the people can be in any city, couldn't think of recursive solution earlier

Actually solve find the number of distinct islands shapes by storing the relative indices of current island path i.e. when doing a DFS add the relative index of the current node to curPath (relative from starting point of the DFS)
Using relative index will help in finding similar shapes

Solve medium find whether a graph is a valid tree or not using
1. DFS + Cycle Detection (Care must be taken to exclude parents as its an undirected graph) 2. Using union find. Thanks to the well explained solution, was able to understand motivation behind path compression with rank in union find operations. Path compression directly connects the descendants to the parent in find_set() operation. Rank is used to merge smaller set to the larger set during union() operation. This allows smaller updates in the tree during find_set() operation.

Solve medium find whether a graph is a valid tree or not using
1. DFS + Cycle Detection (Care must be taken to exclude parents as its an undirected graph) 2. Using union find. Thanks to the well explained solution, was able to understand motivation behind path compression with rank in union find operations. Path compression directly connects the descendants to the parent in find_set() operation. Rank is used to merge smaller set to the larger set during union() operation. This allows smaller updates in the tree during find_set() operation.
Solve medium find number of connected connected in a graph using union find algorithm. Similar to previously solved NumberOfIslands, can also be done using DFS.
Solve medium clone a graph by DFS + keeping a mapping of source node to cloned node, in order to resolve cycles.
